mutant: m051_merge_cleanup_dir_fsync_deleted
target: internal/ingest/orchestrator/merge.go
failure-mode: |
  Merge cleanup removes the data/backfill subtree and then deletes the merge
  cursors, but the data-dir fsync between the unlink and the SyncWrites cursor
  deletes is gone. deleteMergeCursor commits with store.SyncWrites, so the cursor
  deletion is durable immediately while the dirent removal is not. A power loss
  in that window rolls back the removal while keeping the cursor deletion: on
  restart the phase is still PhaseMerging, backfill/live_segments reappears, the
  restart-after-cleanup guard is skipped, and the drain re-runs from cursor 0,
  appending already-merged survivors a second time into data/segments and
  corrupting the archive with duplicate events.
expected-detection: |
  Killed by the powerloss tier's
  TestRunMerge_StrictMemPowerLossCleanupComplete. The test drains a survivor
  (rev above the backfill watermark) into data/segments, fires the
  AfterMergeCleanupComplete crashpoint to simulate a power cut on strict-mem,
  resets to the durable synced state, re-runs runMerge, and requires the
  survivor to appear exactly once. Under this mutant the rolled-back backfill
  tree drives a re-drain and the survivor lands twice (count 2, want 1). The
  default oracle lifecycle does not catch it: without a real power cut the
  data-dir fsync is invisible to normal operation.
expected-tier: powerloss
tiers: powerloss

